and, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pierre","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Pierre DE THINIERES was born in 1230, in Saint-Symphorien-de-Thénières, Aveyron, Occitanie, France as the son of Assalit DE TINNIERES and Catherine DE CASSUEJOULS. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Marie DE LA CHABANNES. He died in 1285, at the age of 55, and was buried in Lanobre, Cantal, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France."},"et":{"1230–1285":"1230–1285","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1250–1309":"1250–1309","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1270–1338":"1270–1338","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1338":"1338","8 janvier 1270":"8. jaanuar 1270","1255":"1255","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","Lanobre, Mauriac, Cantal, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Lanobre, Cantal, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Lanobre, Cantal, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Lanobre, Cantal, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Peyrignac, Sarlat-la-Canéda